{"actual_usd":0.15745,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":278,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30656,"reply":"\"I don't think those explanations carry the weight of the thing, Ryan.\" *I ease a hand over my tie knot and squint a little into the bright square, as if the morning light itself were asking for plain speech.* \"Grief can do strange things to a person, yes. But grief-visions don't usually produce a whole movement of people saying, not merely 'we felt him near,' but 'he was raised' — and then staking their lives on it when that claim could get them beaten, scattered, or killed.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees a moment.* \"And the 'maybe he didn't die' road is worse, honestly. A half-dead man staggering out of a tomb after scourging and crucifixion does not inspire worship of the conqueror of death. He inspires pity, bandages, and a place to lie down.\"\n\n\"The reason Christians insist on the supernatural is that the claim itself is supernatural. Not 'something meaningful happened in their hearts,' but 'God raised Jesus bodily from the dead.'\" *I glance up at the clear sky, then back to you.* \"If you trim that down to something nature can already explain, you've kept a little of the poetry and lost the actual gospel.\"\n\n\"What part of it are you pushing on hardest — the visions theory, or the question of whether miracles can happen at all?\"","rolling_24h_usd":63.169920000000005,"run_id":"078d0b80-480f-4cbc-b4f6-7519574dc5a4"}
